pullRequest.body:
---

Sorry to have merged #8599 hastily! This PR tidies up details like namespacing in that PR. Also, given an additive or multiplicative group `A` with an appropriate scalar action of a group `G`, we define low degree cocycle/coboundary conditions on $Fun(G, A), Fun(G^2, A),$ and then link that up with the existing cocycle/coboundary types for the representation associated to `A`. Using this, `RepresentationTheory.GroupCohomology.Hilbert90` gets clearer.

Lots of `DistribMulAction` and `MulDistribMulAction` stuff here but it seems like they can't be related by `to_additive` afaik.

nodes.body: The module docstring of https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/RepresentationTheory/GroupCohomology/Basic.html#groupCohomology has some broken tex in it, could you also fix that in this PR? or later

Also having `groupCohomology` in lower case just feels off to me for some reason. Was this discussed anywhere?
I guess group cohomology is a term of type `ModuleCat` and not a `Type` but seeing as `ModuleCat` is bundled types I wonder if we should make an exception here

Thanks for the comments! Hopefully the tex is fixed; can't check with `doc-gen` afaik because I'm on windows... And the casing was discussed in #6029, but yeah, I'm not sure I feel the same as I did in that PR. It's not like projection notation works for `groupCohomology` and I can't imagine why I'd use it anyway

Edit: I'll change it back to `GroupCohomology` in a subsequent PR

LGTM, sorry that this was waiting so long now!

I think we usually give it a name like `isMulOneCoboundary_of_isMulOneCocycle_of_aut_to_units`
Can you restate `mem_oneCocycles_iff` etc. as an iff using the predicates introduced above?
Thanks for the comments! I have done this now
It looks like all mentions of Hilbert90 have left this file... please mention it in comments/docstrings.
done, thanks!
I think people use nowadays `<|` more than `$`, but as you prefer.

```suggestion
def oneCoboundariesOfMemRange {f : G → A} (h : f ∈ LinearMap.range (dZero A)) :
```
Not very important.
Do you mean that `f` should be implict and `h` explicit? The other way seems very weird.
I was under the impression that when a hypothesis is used to define something in the lemma statement, it can be left implicit - is this incorrect?
`f` appears in both sides of equality so I'd make it implicit. `h` doesn't appear in RHS so I'd make it explicit, for ease of rewriting from right to left.
I see, thank you!
`f` can be implicit, but as you wish.

I know `f`'s in the type of `hf`, but I feel like I've been annoyed in the past by things with implicit data arguments where I then have to start the proof of some hypothesis with `show...`. I can't remember the context though so it may be irrelevant, and I guess in Lean 4 it's easier to just specify `f` with `(f := ...)` if you want to.
Do you think `x` should also be implicit?
If you find this version more convenient just keep it like that.
Again `f` can be implicit and similarly below.
As above it seems weird. This happens also below.
Same.
Is this lemma autogenerated by `@[mk_iff]`?
Thank you, I didn't know about `@[mk_iff]`. It only applies to inductive declarations, apparently. Maybe I should make `IsOneCocycle` etc a class?
I think you can simply use `rw [IsOneCocycle]` and remove this lemma.
Fair play, will do
Same.

```suggestion
  simpa only [mul_one, one_smul, self_eq_add_right] using (isOneCocycle_iff f).1 hf 1 1
```
untested. If it works you can also remove the `by`. Same below.
This works, thank you. Confused about the `by` comment, though
Does `simpa only [mul_one, one_smul, self_eq_add_right] using hf 1 1` work?
it does, thanks

```suggestion
end IsCocycle

section IsCoboundary

variable {G A : Type*} [Mul G] [AddCommGroup A] [SMul G A]
```
I find it more readable, but do as you prefer.

```suggestion
end ofDistribMulAction

section IsMulCocycle

section

variable {G M : Type*} [Mul G] [CommGroup M] [SMul G M]
```
This section is the same as above but for multiplicative groups, right? If this is the case we probably want a docstring explaining it.
